  "id": "019ce0bf-274e-7273-9b58-604a1d32beb3",
  "content": "# LLM Inference Optimization Techniques: Continuous Batching, PagedAttention, Speculative Decoding\n\n## Continuous Batching (Iteration-Level Batching)\n\nTraditional batching collects N requests and processes them as a group. Short prompts finish early but wait idle for the longest sequence in the batch. Continuous batching inserts new requests into the batch at every decode step as soon as any slot frees up. No request waits for others to finish.\n\n**Relevance to corvia-inference:** Not relevant for local/single-user deployments. Matters at 10+ concurrent requests per GPU. corvia-inference serves one request at a time per model — continuous batching would only matter if corvia-inference evolves into a multi-tenant serving layer.\n\n## PagedAttention\n\nLLM inference maintains a KV cache (key-value attention pairs) for every token generated. Traditional serving pre-allocates contiguous GPU memory for the maximum possible sequence length — most of it wasted. PagedAttention (invented by vLLM, 2023) applies OS-style virtual memory paging: the KV cache is split into fixed-size non-contiguous pages allocated on demand. Result: 2-4x more concurrent sequences in the same GPU memory.\n\n**Relevance to corvia-inference:** Helpful when running large models near VRAM limits (e.g. 7B on 8GB GPU). However, corvia-inference uses GGUF quantization via llama.cpp which solves the same problem differently (smaller model footprint). For corvia's typical use case (embeddings + small chat models), VRAM pressure is low.\n\n## Speculative Decoding\n\nLLM inference is memory-bandwidth bound — the GPU is mostly idle waiting for data transfer during each forward pass. Speculative decoding uses a small \"draft\" model to guess N tokens ahead (cheap), then the large \"target\" model verifies all N guesses in a single parallel forward pass. Correct guesses yield N tokens for ~1 forward pass cost. Typical speedup: 2-3x on generation.\n\n**Relevance to corvia-inference:** This is the one production optimization that genuinely helps single-user local scenarios. llama.cpp supports it via `--draft`. The llama-cpp-2 Rust bindings support it. corvia-inference does not currently wire speculative decoding but could add it as a future enhancement for chat model acceleration.\n\n## Comparison: corvia-inference vs Production Serving\n\n| Technique | vLLM | TGI | Triton | corvia-inference |\n|-----------|------|-----|--------|-----------------|\n| Continuous batching | Yes (core) | Yes | Yes | No (single request) |\n| PagedAttention | Yes (invented it) | Yes | Via TensorRT-LLM | No (GGUF quantization instead) |\n| Speculative decoding | Yes | Yes | Yes | Not yet (llama.cpp supports it) |\n| Per-model device control | No | No | Yes | Yes (runtime switching) |\n| Intel iGPU (OpenVINO) | No | No | Yes | Yes |\n| Mixed embedding+chat | No | No | Yes | Yes |\n\ncorvia-inference is a lightweight local inference sidecar, not a production LLM serving solution. Its differentiators are zero-config deployment, per-model runtime device control, and unified embedding+chat in one process — optimized for developer machines and edge deployments rather than datacenter throughput.",
